<font color="#FF0000">WE NEED TO KNOW</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  8 19:18:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I am 24 years old, a college graduate with a degree in social science.  For as long as I can remember I have always wanted to know as much as I could about Vietnam.  The earliest memory of knowledge was knowing that both of my parents were there, seperately and at different times.  My mother was in the Red Cross and my father in the Air Force. It wasn't until I was in the eight grade that I learned where my father was, when and also that he had medals.  That was my first project on the war.  Since then I have read countless books, done hours or research on both the war and Vietnam as a country.  Yet still, I do not understand.  My father has never again spoken to me about what has happened, likewise my mother.  (Actually he never told me, but filled out a questionaire for my project.)  The veterans I have met since leaving home will not talk about their experiences either.  How can we understand unless you tell us.  How can we avoid another &quot;Vietnam&quot;, unless YOU set the record straight.  I think this website is an excellent place for that dialogue to start and continue.  My dream one day is to teach high school history.  Help me to explain to my students what you went through.  If asked, please tell my generation, the post-war generation, your stories. Help us to understand.
<p><code>-- jdcrouch@cswnet.com  (Mary Ellen Crouch) </code><p>


